The U.S. telecommunications equipment industry is composed of: 1) telephone
and telegraph apparatus; and 2) radio and television broadcasting and
communications equipment.  These two groupings are further subdivided as
follows:

     1) Network equipment: switching and transmission equipment
        Customer premises equipment: telephones and facsimile machines

     2) Fixed and mobile radio systems
        Cellular radio telephones
        Radio transmitters, transceivers, and receivers
           (except household and automotive)
        Fiber optics equipment
        Satellite communication systems: space and ground
        Closed-circuit and cable television equipment
        Studio audio and video equipment

During 1993, U.S. shipments of telecommunications equipment were $35.5
billion, in constant dollars. This level represents virtually no change when
compared to the 1992 level of $35.4 billion, in constant dollars.  This
negligible growth is mainly due to excess capacity in the industry.  Shipments
for group 1 above remained at about $17.5 billion, while shipments for group 2
above increased from $17.8 billion in 1992 to an estimated $18 billion in
1993.

Industry shipments for 1994 are expected to increase by 1% to nearly $36
billion.  Product areas contributing to this growth include network equipment,
wireless communications equipment, and satellite communications.

Until 1993, the industry had been running a trade deficit for many years: $791
million in 1990, $557 million in 1991, $496 million in 1992, before turning a
$578 million surplus in 1993.  U.S. imports increased by nearly 10% to $9.1
billion from $8.3 billion in 1992.  U.S. exports increased by about 24% to
almost $9.7 billion from $7.8 billion in 1992.  The main export markets for
U.S. companies during 1993 were the European Community (18% of total), Mexico
(18% of total) and Canada (14% of total).  Japan, third largest individual
country export market, received an increase of 48% in U.S. products over 1992.
The leading export categories are radio transceivers, parts for radio
equipment, parts for switching equipment, and switching equipment.


