ALGERIA

The telephone company has a long-term plan to modernize and expand its network
and to introduce new services.  Implementation will depend almost entirely
upon imports.  U.S. manufacturers dominate the radio communications and
satellite equipment market, but presence in other areas is very limited.
Sales efforts should be directed to transmission, particularly fiber optics,
switching and broadcasting equipment.  Even though total market size and
imports recently declined, local market analysts foresee new activity.  We
project growth in total market size, imports, and in opportunities for U.S.
companies to increase market share.

Most promising subsectors (Estimated 1993 Market Size in US$ millions):
- Transmission equipment                                            60
- Fiber optics                                                      60
- Radio communications                                              30


ARGENTINA

The Argentine Government continued with its ambitious privatization of the
telecommunications sector.  ENTEL, the Government-owned telephone company, was
transferred to two private groups, Telecom (which includes Stet/France Telecom
and J.P. Morgan Bank), and Telefonica Argentina (grouping Telefonica of Spain
and Citibank). The license to operate these two areas was granted on an
exclusive basis for seven years (until 1997), which may be extended to three
more years (year 2000).  Both telephone companies, however, have procured
U.S.-manufactured equipment up to US$ 60 million in 1992.  This figure will be
increased to US$ 70 million in 1993. The strong local currency and the
economic stability continues to encourage Argentine firms to re-equip
themselves with state-of-the-art telecommunications systems.  This tendency
will be reinforced after 1995, once the rehabilitation and modernization of
hundreds of thousands of telephone lines will consequently demand high-
technology equipment and services.

Most promising subsectors (Estimated 1993 Market Size in US$ millions):
