COSTA RICA

Telecommunication equipment imported by the Costa Rican Institute of
Electricity (ICE), a government entity, is exempt of custom duties and other
local taxes. Products imported by private companies are subject to custom
duties of 22% levied on c.i.f. value. The Costa Rican Central Bank offers
immediate availability of foreign currency for importers. Importers may now
obtain foreign currency from any local bank without previous authorization
from the Central Bank.

The Costa Rican Institute of Electricity (ICE), in charge of the
telecommunication development in the country, is the largest importer of
telecommunication equipment in Costa Rica. According to officials from ICE,
the institution is planning to purchase approximately US$ 71.4 million worth
of telecommunication equipment per year from 1993 trough 1996.
Telecommunication products imported from the U.S. in 1992 represented 34% of
Costa Rican total imports. Principal competitors of U.S. products, especially
telephone lines, are Alcatel of France and Siemmens of Germany.


CZECH REPUBLIC

The Czech telecommunications company, SPT Telecom, will be privatized in 1993-
94.  A foreign partner will be offered 27% of company's stock and will be
allowed to increase the asset value by investment up to 130 percent.  The
state owned portion will not be allowed to drop under 51% without government
approval.  U.S. company J.P. Morgan will advise the government on
telecommunications sector privatization and will also help to run the tender
and selection processes.  The Czech telecommunications sector needs complete
modernization.  The aim of the modernization program is to double the capacity
of the telecommunications network by the year 2000.  The program focuses on
the following issues: 1) installation of local and international digital
switchboards, 2) construction  of a fiber optic cable network, and 3)
development of radiotelephone network and public data network.

