FINLAND

Finland has one of the most open telecommunication markets in Europe.  Both
the subscriber lines and the telephone density are among the highest in the
world.  A special feature of the Finnish telecommunication market is that
there are two key players in the market, Telecom Finland and 49 subscriber-
owned, private telephone companies.  Increasing competition between Telecom
Finland and the private telephone companies, the development of the European
common market and Finland's interest in becoming an EC member have accelerated
the process of telecommunications liberalization.

In 1994 Finland will open local and trunk telephone traffic for competition
between Telecom Finland and the local telephone companies.  In May 1993,
Finland's 49 independent telephone companies submitted an application to the
Ministry of Communications for an international telephone call operating
license.  If the Government of Finland grants the license, this would break
the last telecommunications monopoly in Finland.


Liberalization of Finland's telecommunications has created possibilities for
foreign companies to enter the Finnish market.  Major opportunities for
American companies are in the fields of: network connections, voice
processing, LAN connections, data communication equipment, video conference
systems, etc.  The future trend towards "wireless" offices is also expected to
create possibilities for foreign companies.

At present, Finland has a major program called the "Government Radio Project"
under review.  This $1 billion project would combine networks of police force,
coast guard, customs, civil aviation, safety section of the State railways,
etc.  Depending on government funding, the project is expected to begin in
1996 and be completed by the year 2000.

At present the United States has 10% of imports of telecommunications
equipment.  The strongest competitors are Japan (22.7%), Sweden (22.2%) and
Germany (12.8%).  Finnish manufacturers provide about 50% of local market
needs.  Imports of telecommunications equipment is expected to increase by 10-
15% in volume within the next three years.  The growth in dollars is
considerably less at 8% over the same period due to price discounts.

It should be emphasized that telecommunication equipment to be connected to
the electrical power network must meet the Finnish standards and be examined
and approved by the Electrical Inspectorate.  If the device is connected to
the telephone network, it has to be approved by the Technical Customer Service
of Post and Telecommunications or the Research Institute of Helsinki Telephone
Company.  Finnish distributors are responsible for executing the procedures
involved with testing.  When Finland becomes a member of the European
Community the local approval process will disappear.

