PORTUGAL

Portugal's first private telecommunications company began operations on
October 1992 when a Portuguese-U.S. consortium launched a pan-European
cellular telephone network in the country.  The system operates on 900 mhz
(CEPT/GSM).  The start-up follows the liberalization of the telecommunications
sector.  The Portuguese telecommunications authorities have a massive
investment program to increase the number of communications lines and central
units.  Equipment supplied to this sector conform to CEPT standards.  The
state-owned telecommunications companies will open to the private sector in
1994.  Foreign share holding in telephone companies being privatized are
limited to 25%.  Portugal is rapidly opening up complementary services to
private investors.  Telepoint, DECT (Digital European Cordless Telecom) and
PCN (Personal Communications Network) will be the next tenders.  A Telepoint
license is expected to be announced in 1994.  These figures of continued
growth in Telecommunications equipment imports need to be conditioned to the
fact that American exporters may switch their sourcing of exports to Portugal
from the United States itself to some supply facility within the EC.  As a
consequence American brand equipment will, in fact, continue to rise but
direct exports from the U.S. of same may decline.

