RUSSIA

The telecommunications sector improved significantly in 1992.  Although Russia
is 20 to 30 years behind Western countries in the development of its
telecommunications infrastructure, it is ahead of Eastern European countries.
U.S. and European companies have more or less filled the demand for
international telecommunications services in Moscow and St. Petersburg.

During 1990-1992, the Russian Ministry of Communications issued more than 150
licenses to foreign firms to provide telecommunications services, including 57
for international operations; 33 for data transmission; and 34 for mobile
telephone and paging services.

Due to the growing number of foreign firms willing to participate in the
development of local telecommunications networks, the Russian Ministry of
Communications made a decision to request tenders from them.  Regional
officials now have more rights to lobby the Ministry of Communications to
issue operational licenses for a particular company or project in their
region.

The Russian Government and PTT have worked out a strategic plan for the
development of an integrated international communications infrastructure.  The
ground part of it includes 14,000 kilometers of fiber optic trunk lines
between Russia-Western Europe; Russia-Southern Europe; Russia-Japan; Russia-
South Korea.  The satellite part of the plan involves four major projects
which will provide reliable communications between remote areas of Russia as
well as international links.  U.S. telecommunications companies are encouraged
to participate in these projects, supplying telecommunications equipment,
technology, and services.  Russia estimates the costs for the development of
an efficient communications network to be US$ 60 billion.

As part of the U.S. Department of Commerce CABNIS program, the U.S.
Telecommunications Industry Association established a representative office in
early Summer 1993.  The activities of the consortium are expected to increase
sales of U.S. telecommunications equipment in Russia and the NIS.

