THAILAND

Thailand recognizes that weaknesses in the telecommunications infrastructure
have hindered national economic development. Telecommunications has
traditionally been a state enterprise monopoly in Thailand with one state
enterprise responsible for domestic telecommunications services (Telephone
Organization of Thailand -- TOT) and one for international (Communications
Authority of Thailand -- CAT). Market demand and rapid advances in
communications and information technology, have compelled the Thai Government
to open doors for the private sector to participate in new telecommunications
plans -- largely through the offering of long term concessions to private
firms for various telecommunications services. Recent concession agreements
include one awarded to the TelecomAsia Company to install 2 million phone
lines in the Bangkok metropolitan area, one to Thai Telephone &
Telecommunication Company to install one million phone lines in provincial
areas, one to Shinawatra Computer Company for a satellite, and an optical
fiber project awarded to Com Link Company. Major concessions include (1) the
second international telephone switching center, (2) the fiber optic submarine
cable project Phase I, Phase II and Phase III, (3) mobile land sea and air
communications Phase I, and (4) the teleport project at the Eastern Seaboard
Development zone in the ports of Laem Chabang and Mab Ta Phut.

