UKRAINE

Ukraine's poor and outdated local telecommunications system will be familiar
to anyone who has ever had the experience of using a telephone in the former
Soviet Union.  With a population of 52 million, Ukraine has 963 local
networks, including 1,215 automatic telephone exchanges with a total capacity
of 7 million subscribers and approximately 13 telephones per 100 people.  The
national telecommunications development plan calls for the number of
subscribers to increase to 9 million by 1995, which will require an estimated
investment of US$ 234.6 million.  Long-distance service is provided by UTEL, a
joint venture including AT&T, Siemens, Dutch PTT and the Ukrainian Ministry of
Communications. AT&T has also created two joint ventures for production of
telecommunications equipment in Ukraine.  The country still has a long way to
go to reach normal European standards for telephone services.  As foreign
investment grows and the standard of living rises in this young country the
demand for telecommunications equipment and services will outpace supply and
create opportunities for a wide range of equipment and service suppliers.

